class="content"><p
from
young
age
idania
rodriguez
understood
just
how
important
it
was
to
be
confident
outspoken
and
to
advocate
for
herself
and
others.</p><p
rodriguez
learned
from
watching
her
parents
fight
to
build
new
life
for
their
three
children
moving
from
puerto
rico
to
tampa
florida
was
nt
an
easy
transition
at
times
her
family
struggled
to
make
ends
meet
but
their
strength
and
perseverance
never
wavered.</p><p
from
their
example
rodriguez
learned
how
to
harness
her
own
voice
and
to
use
it
to
help
people
around
her.</p><p
rodriguez
first
year
carolina
student
founded
the
nonprofit
mental
H2O
when
she
was
inspired
by
the
mental
health
issues
of
her
peers
especially
during
the
COVID-19
pandemic
rodriguez
sought
to
create
an
information
hub
designed
by
youth
for
youth.</p><p
during
school
realized
that
sometimes
mental
health
is
not
really
talked
about
rodriguez
said
there
would
be
students
that
were
struggling
in
silence
or
that
were
afraid
to
come
out
and
say
their
feelings
because
they
were
afraid
of
how
an
adult
would
take
that
information.</p><p
myself
struggled
with
my
own
mental
health
issues
and
realized
that
its
really
difficult
to
receive
help
in
school
that
when
started
to
realize
that
we
had
gap
to
fill
and
if
no
adult
was
going
to
take
stand
knew
that
had
to.</p><p
determined
to
make
difference
rodriguez
pored
over
online
resources
about
mental
health
and
in
the
process
connected
with
fellow
mental
health
advocate
and
current
kenan
flagler
business
school
student
garrett
livingston.</p><p
together
rodriguez
and
livingston
worked
through
the
process
of
registering
mental
H2O
as
501(c)(3
organization
and
creating
website
with
rodriguez
serving
as
president
and
livingston
as
ceo.</p><p
the
mental
H2O
website
started
small
rodriguez
wrote
most
of
the
sites
articles
at
first
coming
home
from
school
around
p.m.
and
working
deep
into
the
evening
before
long
rodriguez
rallied
about
of
her
classmates
to
contribute
then
started
collaborating
with
her
local
school
board
in
hillsborough
county
now
the
site
has
more
than
volunteers
worldwide
and
has
awarded
more
than
1,000
service
hours.</p><p
the
mental
H2O
website
is
filled
with
mental
health
resources
tips
and
tools
all
curated
by
students.</p><p
every
single
resource
on
there
is
actually
created
by
students
for
students
and
were
very
cautious
about
what
we
put
on
the
site
rodriguez
said
know
that
it
can
be
really
difficult
to
receive
help
making
sure
it
is
culturally
sensitive
and
also
addressing
the
needs
of
the
students
was
very
important
from
the
beginning.</p><p
the
work
is
only
getting
started
emboldened
by
the
feedback
she
received
and
the
impact
mental
H2O
has
made
on
her
tampa
community
rodriguez
aims
to
sharpen
her
skills
at
carolina
and
grow
into
even
more
of
leader
in
the
mental
health
space.</p><p
rodriguez
intends
to
apply
to
the
gillings
school
of
global
public
health
and
major
in
health
policy
and
management
she
said
she
chose
to
study
at
carolina
in
part
because
of
the
schools
commitment
to
student
wellness.</p><p
did
nt
want
to
go
to
college
that
did
not
prioritize
student
needs
or
that
did
not
prioritize
student
wellness
rodriguez
said.</p><p
unc
definitely
does
do
that
and
that
why
feel
like
can
drive
bigger
audience
and
can
utilize
what
unc
has
to
offer
to
further
push
my
mission
of
helping
students
with
their
mental
health.</p><div
